1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,920
 Welcome back.

2
00:00:00,920 --> 00:00:03,920
 So let's talk about some of the basic syntax of HTML.

3
00:00:03,920 --> 00:00:07,720
 The first thing is to look at the overall document layout.

4
00:00:07,720 --> 00:00:10,120
 And they start with an HTML tag.

5
00:00:10,120 --> 00:00:14,720
 You might have a thing called a doctype up here, and we can put in one if we like.

6
00:00:14,720 --> 00:00:19,640
 But HTML is the outer tag, and then there is a head tag and an end head tag.

7
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:21,720
 And this is sort of non-printing information.

8
00:00:21,720 --> 00:00:27,280
 We set styling up, we declare the title of a page, perhaps load some JavaScript.

9
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:31,400
 And then the printable page of the content is in between a body tag.

10
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:36,520
 And mostly what we're gonna talk about is the stuff that we put in as page content.

11
00:00:36,520 --> 00:00:42,680
 So you'll find that there are special file names that we use.

12
00:00:42,680 --> 00:00:45,480
 It really has to do with the fact that what we do is we make a directory within

13
00:00:45,480 --> 00:00:46,840
 the web server.

14
00:00:46,840 --> 00:00:50,360
 And when we go visit the directory,

15
00:00:50,360 --> 00:00:54,360
 the web server looks through a series of files that it's configured to look to.

16
00:00:54,360 --> 00:00:57,920
 Things like index.html, index.htm, or index.php, and

17
00:00:57,920 --> 00:01:02,000
 each one has a slightly different order and a slightly different set of things.

18
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,160
 It might even be called default.htm or default.asp if you're on a Windows box.

19
00:01:07,160 --> 00:01:10,760
 It is configurable, so different systems do things differently.

20
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:15,600
 But usually index.htm is probably the safest thing unless you're doing php,

21
00:01:15,600 --> 00:01:18,080
 which we will be doing later in index.php.

22
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:21,040
 And so those are usually the safe bet.

23
00:01:21,040 --> 00:01:24,600
 Now when you're viewing things off of disk, which we can do, if you download all

24
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:30,760
 the code that I've got in HTML.zip, then you'll have to open the index.html by hand.

25
00:01:30,760 --> 00:01:34,680
 So we can put multiple files in the same directory, and

26
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:37,160
 then we can use them in what are called relative links.

27
00:01:37,160 --> 00:01:40,760
 And so we can easily create links between one file and another.

28
00:01:40,760 --> 00:01:43,240
 And so you'll tend to see, if you look at the zip file,

29
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:46,840
 that you've got a whole bunch of files in the same directory.

30
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:51,560
 And with little anchor tags, they point back and forth between each one.

31
00:01:51,560 --> 00:01:56,000
 And so, like I said, you got tags, like the paragraph tag, the strong tag,

32
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:57,360
 and the emphasize tag.

33
00:01:57,360 --> 00:01:59,240
 They have to start, they have to stop.

34
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:04,280
 But another thing that's really important about HTML is the fact that

35
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:07,680
 most of the time we are logically marking up the text.

36
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:12,160
 And so we're saying we want this stuff right here to be a paragraph.

37
00:02:12,160 --> 00:02:16,000
 But the end of the lines that we put in the HTML that we write are not really

38
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:17,200
 that important.

39
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:19,520
 What happens is, is depending on the width of the browser,

40
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:25,880
 if you change the width of the browser, the text will be rewrapped.

41
00:02:25,880 --> 00:02:30,040
 And that's because there's still a paragraph, but

42
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:33,400
 we don't wanna hard code it, cuz we're not working on paper.

43
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:36,840
 Sometimes browsers are really large, sometimes browsers are really small.

44
00:02:36,840 --> 00:02:38,800
 Sometimes you're on a phone, right?

45
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:40,760
 And on a phone, browser's really small.

46
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:45,640
 And so you don't want to tell exactly how many pixels it is wide,

47
00:02:45,640 --> 00:02:47,640
 except when you start doing really fancy layout.

48
00:02:47,640 --> 00:02:49,320
 But in things like paragraphs, you just say, hey,

49
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:51,200
 make it a paragraph and re-wrap it.

50
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:55,480
 And the re-wrapping then also changes how tall the pages are,

51
00:02:55,480 --> 00:02:58,920
 because the narrower pages kind of extends the page down.

52
00:02:58,920 --> 00:03:03,460
 But the white space inside of the HTML is really generally ignored, and

53
00:03:03,460 --> 00:03:04,640
 the lines are generally ignored.

54
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:07,840
 There are some tags, like the pre-tag, that changes that.

55
00:03:07,840 --> 00:03:11,920
 So white space is respected, and new lines are respected.

56
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:15,440
 But most of the time, we just let the browser re-wrap things.

57
00:03:15,440 --> 00:03:15,940
 And it's good.

58
00:03:15,940 --> 00:03:19,280
 You have beginning tags and ending tags.

59
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:21,720
 So here's a beginning tag, and then here's the ending tag.

60
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:25,320
 The slash is our indication of an ending, and they're paired.

61
00:03:25,320 --> 00:03:26,200
 And they're also nested.

62
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:30,520
 So this p tag has a strong tag within it and an m tag within it, and

63
00:03:30,520 --> 00:03:33,760
 that's totally okay, because this whole thing is a paragraph, and

64
00:03:33,760 --> 00:03:35,480
 this is a piece of bold text.

65
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:38,120
 So they have beginning and end, and slash is the end.

66
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:44,360
 You can also have self-closing tags that have an image tag

67
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:48,520
 that has a slash, and that means that you don't have to have a slash image over here.

68
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:51,320
 That's the same, you just put a slash here and it self-closes.

69
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:55,760
 Another thing that you will get used to is the fact that you can put on

70
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:59,400
 the opening tag attributes, so key value pairs.

71
00:03:59,400 --> 00:04:03,120
 And you'll go define what the, you'll go to the documentation on the image tag and

72
00:04:03,120 --> 00:04:06,880
 it'll say, put a source attribute on to say what picture,

73
00:04:06,880 --> 00:04:09,400
 what file we want to display as the picture.

74
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:11,840
 The image tag is to show pictures, basically.

75
00:04:13,720 --> 00:04:15,760
 So given that less than and greater than and

76
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:18,280
 other things are special characters,

77
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:21,280
 we have to have a way to print the special characters.

78
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:23,720
 So how do we print a special character?

79
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:28,720
 Well, we use ampersand LT semicolon, and there's a whole list of these things.

80
00:04:28,720 --> 00:04:33,720
 HTML special characters, and you can look them up.

81
00:04:33,720 --> 00:04:38,800
 And you don't, there's some that are kind of fun, like the special characters for

82
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:42,600
 the deck of the cards, there's mathematical special characters.

83
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:44,640
 And you go look these up and you can find them.

84
00:04:44,640 --> 00:04:46,760
 The key thing is you don't, they're cute and

85
00:04:46,760 --> 00:04:49,520
 you'll see that I'll use some of these arrows in the things that I'm doing.

86
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:54,160
 But the key ones that you really need to know about are less than greater than and

87
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,160
 ampersand.

88
00:04:55,160 --> 00:04:59,280
 And just because ampersand becomes a special character, less than greater than or

89
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:02,440
 ampersand are really the special characters in HTML.

90
00:05:02,440 --> 00:05:08,160
 And so to represent less than, you do ampersand LT, ampersand GT, and

91
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:12,800
 ampersand ampersand, and P semicolon to get those things right.

92
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:16,960
 HTML comments, like in any programming language, any situation,

93
00:05:16,960 --> 00:05:22,160
 the start of an HTML comment is less than exclamation dash dash.

94
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:26,840
 It's a little clunky, but we just wanna make sure it's really clear.

95
00:05:26,840 --> 00:05:31,240
 And so dash dash less than, comments can go across many lines,

96
00:05:31,240 --> 00:05:32,640
 if that's what you wanna do.

97
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:33,720
 So that works as well.

98
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:39,520
 Links is a critical element of HTML, it's why search engines work.

99
00:05:39,520 --> 00:05:43,880
 It's why when I first saw it, I'm like, I click on a thing and

100
00:05:43,880 --> 00:05:45,720
 there's a new page, isn't that amazing, right?

101
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:51,560
 And so hyperlinks is the H in HTML, it's the H in HTTP.

102
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:57,080
 And so it is how we in effect use this thing that we're sort of just scribbling

103
00:05:57,080 --> 00:05:59,800
 on to create knowledge that Google then can extract.

104
00:06:01,520 --> 00:06:07,320
 And so the anchor tag, the a tag, is the tag that we use to do these things.

105
00:06:07,320 --> 00:06:10,520
 And so there's a header one, a paragraph, and

106
00:06:10,520 --> 00:06:14,480
 the anchor tag has, this is the start tag, and this is the end tag.

107
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:17,400
 And so the text that's clickable is second page.

108
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:19,440
 And you can see that it's clickable right there.

109
00:06:19,440 --> 00:06:25,520
 It is styled with a underline and blue to indicate that it's a link.

110
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:29,480
 And so there is the href, which stands for hypertext reference.

111
00:06:29,480 --> 00:06:33,640
 And then it's an attribute, so it's key value with double quotes.

112
00:06:33,640 --> 00:06:35,120
 And then this is another URL.

113
00:06:35,120 --> 00:06:37,960
 And so that's like, in effect, putting that URL up and

114
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:40,760
 going into that next page, so it's a hot spot.

115
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:45,240
 In the early days, and I'll show you a few of these,

116
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:48,360
 these links were like the coolest thing ever.

117
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:53,880
 And so we made them pretty colors, like the blue with the dash.

118
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:56,720
 People didn't sort of, when they first saw the web,

119
00:06:56,720 --> 00:07:00,360
 they didn't know to click places, so we sort of styled them quite brightly.

120
00:07:00,360 --> 00:07:04,720
 And then because you were often scanning and searching the whole web,

121
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:06,320
 cuz the web wasn't so big in the beginning,

122
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:09,920
 we would mark them as purple after you'd been to it.

123
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:13,720
 So you could sort of slowly but surely work your way through the whole internet

124
00:07:13,720 --> 00:07:16,960
 as it existed back in the old days, and keep track of the ones so

125
00:07:16,960 --> 00:07:20,120
 you didn't have to go back to the ones that you'd seen before.

126
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:30,560
 And that was an absolute link, and here's one with a relative link.

127
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:33,120
 And that assumes that we are now in the same folder,

128
00:07:33,120 --> 00:07:36,560
 same directory on the server, where we have a href.

129
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:39,440
 And so here's the start tag, here's the end tag, and

130
00:07:39,440 --> 00:07:41,680
 then first page is the clickable stuff.

131
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:45,880
 And you'll note that that is a purple link, because I have already been there,

132
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:49,800
 because page1.htm was exactly where I just came from.

133
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:52,320
 And so you click on that, and then you can go back and forth.

134
00:07:52,320 --> 00:07:57,180
 And those are the pages we played with in the HTTP lecture.

135
00:07:57,180 --> 00:08:01,320
 And so these absolute references are references that start with HTTP or

136
00:08:01,320 --> 00:08:05,240
 HTTPS or whatever, and relative references don't.

137
00:08:05,240 --> 00:08:09,960
 And so that basically means that this page1.htm file has to be in the same

138
00:08:09,960 --> 00:08:14,480
 folder as whatever file we happen to be viewing right now on the same server.

139
00:08:14,480 --> 00:08:17,080
 So if you wanna switch folders or switch servers,

140
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:19,080
 you have to use absolute references.

141
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:22,200
 And if you are just moving between files on the same server,

142
00:08:22,200 --> 00:08:24,040
 you can use relative references.

143
00:08:24,040 --> 00:08:33,200
 Images are a lot of fun, and CSS will see how to wrap text.

144
00:08:33,200 --> 00:08:35,520
 One of my favorite things was to wrap text.

145
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:39,360
 There is an image tag, which we saw before, image, and

146
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:43,400
 then the source equals is the attribute, and then it quotes the name of the file.

147
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:47,320
 And it can either be an image that's all by itself.

148
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:50,360
 In this case, this paragraph is what we're seeing.

149
00:08:50,360 --> 00:08:52,720
 And you can see that this image is a tiny image, but

150
00:08:52,720 --> 00:08:54,520
 it's sort of like, blah, blah, blah, blah.

151
00:08:54,520 --> 00:08:56,520
 The image right here works kinda like a character.

152
00:08:56,520 --> 00:08:58,760
 You gotta be careful, cuz the images can be really big.

153
00:08:58,760 --> 00:09:00,480
 That's why I made a tiny image.

154
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:04,760
 And you could even, for example, in this case, I have an anchor tag.

155
00:09:04,760 --> 00:09:10,520
 And the clickable part of the anchor tag is an image.

156
00:09:10,520 --> 00:09:16,360
 So if you click right there, that will move you to lists.htm.

157
00:09:16,360 --> 00:09:18,960
 And so you can make an image be a hypertext reference as well.

158
00:09:18,960 --> 00:09:20,760
 Now we're gonna do much more with these things, and

159
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:24,060
 this is just, at this point, the basics.

160
00:09:24,060 --> 00:09:27,440
 Lists are an important part of HTML.

161
00:09:27,440 --> 00:09:30,520
 There's ordered lists and unordered lists.

162
00:09:30,520 --> 00:09:36,440
 And so the unordered list starts with a UL tag and ends with a UL tag.

163
00:09:36,440 --> 00:09:39,960
 And then that sort of bounds the whole list.

164
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:46,880
 And then each list element starts with an li, list item, and /li.

165
00:09:46,880 --> 00:09:48,400
 And I want a little bit of spacing.

166
00:09:48,400 --> 00:09:51,760
 If you don't put them in paragraphs, you don't quite get the default spacing.

167
00:09:51,760 --> 00:09:54,280
 This blank line's really coming from the paragraphs.

168
00:09:54,280 --> 00:09:56,480
 So I'm putting a list of paragraphs, basically.

169
00:09:56,480 --> 00:09:58,640
 It doesn't have to be a list of paragraphs.

170
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:02,840
 You could make a little denser list with a list of links or something.

171
00:10:02,840 --> 00:10:05,000
 But I'm putting paragraphs in.

172
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:09,840
 And so you can see that I have li to end li, li to end li.

173
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:12,440
 I'm putting some links in here, etc, etc.

174
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:15,320
 And so dot, dot, dot, dot, and it puts all the bullets in.

175
00:10:15,320 --> 00:10:17,440
 It does the indenting automatically.

176
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:20,600
 We'll see in a bit how we can control all that formatting and

177
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:23,040
 do different things if we wanna do those different things.

178
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:27,000
 But for now, we're just going to play with the default formatting and

179
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,840
 learn the HTML, which is our way of representing that we wanna list on

180
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:34,640
 the screen, but we're not so fancy about exactly how it's supposed to look.

181
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:38,160
 So in HTML, we really are looking for the meaning of the page,

182
00:10:38,160 --> 00:10:39,240
 not how pretty it is.

183
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:44,720
 Tables, tables have a bit of a checkered past.

184
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:50,200
 In the early days, people tended to use tables to lay pages out on grids.

185
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:53,440
 And they would just put a paragraph here, and a paragraph here, and

186
00:10:53,440 --> 00:10:54,440
 then a paragraph underneath it.

187
00:10:54,440 --> 00:10:55,840
 And they would move them around, and

188
00:10:55,840 --> 00:10:58,640
 they would put images in some of the table cells.

189
00:10:58,640 --> 00:11:00,640
 And that turned out to be really bad.

190
00:11:00,640 --> 00:11:04,760
 And that notion of tables as graphic layout is long gone.

191
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:07,160
 And we use CSS now, which is the next lecture.

192
00:11:07,160 --> 00:11:12,480
 So but tables were always a good idea for tabular data.

193
00:11:12,480 --> 00:11:17,600
 And so if you have something that sort of makes sense is like a list of cars with

194
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:21,960
 some make model mileage columns and a list, then you mark them up.

195
00:11:21,960 --> 00:11:24,560
 And so the table markup is pretty straightforward.

196
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:26,880
 We start a table with the table tag.

197
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:31,920
 And then we have a series of rows using the tr tag, tr to /tr.

198
00:11:31,920 --> 00:11:36,480
 And then if there's a header line, which can be formatted a little bit different,

199
00:11:36,480 --> 00:11:38,920
 we do a th to /th.

200
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:42,160
 And then this basically says it's gonna be a three column table because we have

201
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:44,480
 three table headers, one, two, three.

202
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:46,440
 And then we're gonna put TDs for the data.

203
00:11:46,440 --> 00:11:50,160
 TD stands for data, one, two, three.

204
00:11:50,160 --> 00:11:54,960
 And so that's the Ford, Edge, and then the mileage of that, and on, and on, and on,

205
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,480
 and on as we go.

206
00:11:56,480 --> 00:11:58,400
 And so it's not hard to build them.

207
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:01,600
 You kind of have to keep track of how many of these things you've got.

208
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:07,760
 And there are tricks where you can make a table that has like four things, but

209
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:12,200
 then in one row, this expands so that that's, I can't erase it, can't erase it.

210
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:18,160
 So there are ways to do things where a data element spans more than one column.

211
00:12:18,160 --> 00:12:23,920
 Call span, for example, but the key to tables is that we use them for tables.

212
00:12:23,920 --> 00:12:25,520
 We don't use them for

213
00:12:25,520 --> 00:12:29,360
 arranging things that are not themselves row, row, row, row, row.

214
00:12:29,360 --> 00:12:33,560
 So I'm gonna stop there.

215
00:12:33,560 --> 00:12:38,760
 I'm gonna record some exploration of some sample code at

216
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:44,000
 www.wafore.webapplicationsforeverybody.com/code/html.

217
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:49,040
 And I really am intending that you will, these are very simple pages, but

218
00:12:49,040 --> 00:12:52,440
 the idea is to look at them in developer mode and take a look at them.

219
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:55,440
 And then you can see how the various things work.

220
00:12:55,440 --> 00:13:00,760
 And you can also then look at the source code and see, here's how a pre-tag works.

221
00:13:00,760 --> 00:13:02,640
 Or where's the pre-tag?

222
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:09,440
 No, yeah.

223
00:13:09,440 --> 00:13:13,560
 So look at the source code, take a look at things, and

224
00:13:13,560 --> 00:13:15,760
 show that the line wrapping does not actually matter.

225
00:13:15,760 --> 00:13:17,600
 We look at pre-tag in another one.

226
00:13:17,600 --> 00:13:20,640
 So I'll record some walkthroughs of all this sample code, but

227
00:13:20,640 --> 00:13:24,120
 I encourage you to take a look at it cuz it has a lot of good examples of

228
00:13:24,120 --> 00:13:25,360
 the basics of HTML.

229
00:13:25,360 --> 00:13:29,060
 And so HTML is a continually evolving thing.

230
00:13:29,060 --> 00:13:30,360
 It's a very creative space.

231
00:13:30,360 --> 00:13:31,560
 It's a lot of fun.

232
00:13:31,560 --> 00:13:36,340
